%===============================================================================
% Abstract
%===============================================================================
\begin{abstract}
Electricity markets rely on operating reserve procurement to manage uncertainty arising from renewable generation. This paper develops a differentiable, learning-based robust optimization framework in which the geometry of ellipsoidal uncertainty sets is learned end-to-end from data. The framework profiles the bilevel problem---minimizing robust dispatch cost subject to coverage constraints---into a single-level objective, and derives the profiled gradient including a quantile-sensitivity correction term. For unknown distributions, a four-way data split (train/tune/calibrate/test) enables gradient approximation while achieving finite-sample coverage under exchangeability via split conformal prediction, with empirical validation under temporal dependence; no differentiation through the optimization solver is required. Two structural regimes are identified: zonal reserve formulations admit closed-form support-function derivatives (dual multipliers are obtained from the SCED LP solve), while network-constrained formulations require envelope gradients from dual information. The framework is demonstrated on the IEEE~118-bus system under two dispatch formulations---decoupled zonal reserves and coupled network with inter-zone transfer constraints---showing that learned static correlation structure reduces dispatch cost by 4--5\% while maintaining empirical coverage above the target level.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Robust optimization, uncertainty sets, operating reserves, machine learning, conformal prediction, electricity markets.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

%===============================================================================
% I. Introduction
%===============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

\IEEEPARstart{E}{lectricity} markets rely on operating reserve procurement and pricing mechanisms to manage uncertainty arising from high penetrations of wind and solar generation. Renewable forecast errors exhibit strong spatial and temporal correlations due to common weather patterns~\cite{hodge2011wind,pinson2013wind}. When such correlations are ignored, reserve capacity may be inefficiently allocated, leading to excessive costs and distorted price signals.

Robust optimization provides a principled framework for incorporating uncertainty into power system operations~\cite{ben2009robust,bertsimas2011theory}. In security-constrained economic dispatch (SCED), uncertain parameters are assumed to lie within a prescribed \emph{uncertainty set}, and the dispatch must remain feasible for all realizations within this set. The geometry of the uncertainty set fundamentally determines the conservatism and cost of the solution~\cite{bertsimas2013adaptive}.

\subsection{Literature Review}

\emph{A) Robust Optimization for Power Systems.}
Robust methods have been widely adopted for unit commitment and economic dispatch. Bertsimas et al.~\cite{bertsimas2013adaptive} developed adaptive robust optimization for security-constrained unit commitment with polyhedral uncertainty sets. Jiang et al.~\cite{jiang2012robust} proposed two-stage robust unit commitment, and Zeng and Zhao~\cite{zeng2013solving} introduced column-and-constraint generation. Lorca et al.~\cite{lorca2016multistage} extended these to multistage settings, while Jabr~\cite{jabr2013adjustable} developed adjustable robust OPF with ellipsoidal sets. These approaches assume fixed uncertainty set geometry determined a priori.

\emph{B) Data-Driven and Distributionally Robust Approaches.}
Bertsimas et al.~\cite{bertsimas2018datadriven} proposed data-driven robust optimization using hypothesis testing to calibrate set size. Distributionally robust optimization (DRO) optimizes over ambiguity sets: Mohajerin Esfahani and Kuhn~\cite{esfahani2018data} developed Wasserstein DRO with tractable reformulations, Gao and Kleywegt~\cite{gao2023distributionally} established finite-sample guarantees, and Van Parys et al.~\cite{vanparys2021data} proved asymptotic optimality. In power systems, Xiong et al.~\cite{xiong2017distributionally} applied moment-based DRO to unit commitment. Roald et al.~\cite{roald2023power} survey optimization under uncertainty in power systems. These methods do not directly optimize uncertainty set geometry for downstream costs.

\emph{C) Decision-Focused Learning and Differentiable Optimization.}
Decision-focused learning integrates prediction and optimization by training models to minimize downstream decision cost. Elmachtoub and Grigas~\cite{elmachtoub2022smart} introduced the SPO+ loss, and Donti et al.~\cite{donti2017task} proposed task-based end-to-end learning via KKT differentiation. Differentiable optimization layers~\cite{amos2017optnet,agrawal2019differentiable} enable backpropagation through convex programs, and Bolte et al.~\cite{bolte2021nonsmooth} extended this to nonsmooth settings. Our envelope-based approach avoids differentiating through solvers entirely.

\emph{D) Learned Uncertainty Sets.}
Wang et al.~\cite{wang2023learning} proposed learning decision-focused uncertainty sets via implicit differentiation. Chenreddy and Delage~\cite{chenreddy2024end} developed end-to-end conditional robust optimization. Goerigk and Kurtz~\cite{goerigk2023data} used neural networks to predict uncertainty set parameters. Our work differs in three key respects: (i) envelope gradients avoid differentiating through the solver; (ii) conformal calibration provides distribution-free coverage; and (iii) a profiled gradient with quantile-sensitivity correction accounts for shape--size coupling.

\emph{E) Conformal Prediction.}
Conformal prediction~\cite{vovk2005algorithmic} provides distribution-free uncertainty quantification under exchangeability. Romano et al.~\cite{romano2019conformalized} developed conformalized quantile regression, and Angelopoulos and Bates~\cite{angelopoulos2023conformal} provide a comprehensive tutorial. Johnstone and Cox~\cite{johnstone2021conformal} connected conformal prediction to robust optimization via Mahalanobis distance. Our work extends this by learning the ellipsoid shape end-to-end while preserving conformal coverage through a four-way data split.

\emph{F) Renewable Forecast Uncertainty.}
Wind and solar forecast errors exhibit complex spatial and temporal correlations~\cite{hodge2011wind,pinson2013wind}. Hong and Fan~\cite{hong2016probabilistic} surveyed probabilistic load forecasting. These works motivate the need for correlation-aware uncertainty sets that adapt to varying forecast error patterns---precisely what our learned Cholesky parameterization provides.

\subsection{Contributions}

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Profiled Bilevel Formulation with Envelope Gradients.}
A bilevel framework using gauge-based uncertainty sets is profiled into a single-level objective, and envelope/Clarke gradients are derived from optimal dual multipliers---avoiding differentiation through the solver. The profiled gradient includes a quantile-sensitivity correction term.

\item \textbf{Tuning-Based Gradient Approximation with Distribution-Free Coverage.}
A four-way data split (train/tune/calibrate/test) with smoothed CDF estimation provides a consistent gradient estimator. Conformal calibration provides finite-sample coverage under exchangeability; empirical coverage is validated on a held-out test period.

\item \textbf{Energy Dispatch Application with Two Formulations.}
Instantiation on the IEEE~118-bus system with two dispatch formulations---decoupled zonal reserves and coupled network with inter-zone transfer constraints---demonstrates 4--5\% cost reduction through task-aware learning, with conformal calibration coverage maintained by construction in both regimes; test coverage for the static method exceeds the target in both.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Paper Organization}

Section~\ref{sec:formulation} presents the problem formulation. Section~\ref{sec:methodology} develops the methodology. Section~\ref{sec:algorithm} presents the static and context-dependent training algorithms. Section~\ref{sec:application} instantiates the framework on the IEEE~118-bus system with two dispatch formulations. Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses practical implications. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes.

