Tables~\ref{tab:system-params}--\ref{tab:zones} summarize the IEEE~118-bus test system. We model uncertainty with $d = 15$ dimensions representing three source types (load, solar, wind) across five geographic regions, with an allocation matrix $A \in \R^{10 \times 15}$ aggregating source-level uncertainty to 10 zonal reserve requirements. Context features $\bxi \in \R^7$ include normalized load, solar, and wind forecasts plus cyclical time encodings (hour and month).

\textbf{Data Generation.} Uncertainty samples are generated synthetically from a context-dependent covariance model calibrated to real forecast error data. Two data sources inform the model:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Germany OPSD:} Source-type correlations (load, solar, wind), AR(1) persistence coefficients, and variance scaling profiles.
\item \emph{US Multi-ISO:} Spatial correlations across five system operators (CAISO, ERCOT, PJM, MISO, NYISO), mapped to five geographic regions.
\end{itemize}
The 15-dimensional covariance $\Sigma(\bxi) = D(\bxi) R(\bxi) D(\bxi)$ decomposes into:
\begin{itemize}
\item A diagonal scaling matrix $D(\bxi)$ where marginal standard deviations vary with context: solar variance is near zero at night and proportional to forecast during the day; wind variance scales sublinearly with forecast; load variance scales linearly with forecast.
\item A correlation matrix $R(\bxi) = R_{\mathrm{source}}(\bxi) \otimes R_{\mathrm{region}}$ where the $3 \times 3$ source-type correlation is perturbed by context (e.g., high solar forecast strengthens solar--wind anticorrelation) and the $5 \times 5$ regional correlation is fixed.
\end{itemize}
Uncertainty samples are drawn from a VAR(1) process with context-dependent innovations, and the ground-truth Cholesky factor $\bL_{\mathrm{true}}(\bxi_t)$ is computed for each hour $t$. This provides a benchmark for evaluating whether learned uncertainty sets recover the true correlation structure.

The dataset comprises 35{,}040 hourly samples (4~years), split chronologically: 60\% training (21{,}024), 20\% tuning (7{,}008), 10\% calibration (3{,}504), and 10\% testing (3{,}504). Target coverage is $\tau = 0.95$. The four-way split ensures that shape optimization ($\cD_{\text{train}}$), quantile sensitivity estimation ($\cD_{\text{tune}}$), conformal radius calibration ($\cD_{\text{cal}}$), and out-of-sample evaluation ($\cD_{\text{test}}$) use disjoint data.

\subsection{Methods}

Four approaches for constructing $\cU_{\bL,\rho}$, all evaluated under split conformal calibration:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Independent.} $\bL = \diag(\hat\sigma_1, \ldots, \hat\sigma_d)$ from marginal standard deviations of $\cD_{\text{train}}$. Ignores all cross-dimensional correlations.

\item \textbf{Sample Covariance.} $\bL = \chol(\hat\Sigma)$ from the sample covariance of $\cD_{\text{train}}$. Captures pairwise correlations but is not optimized for dispatch cost.

\item \textbf{Learned (Static).} A single $\bL \in \R^{d \times d}$ trained via Algorithm~\ref{alg:main} to minimize SCED cost, initialized from Sample Covariance.

\item \textbf{Learned (Contextual).} An MLP encoder $\bL_\phi(\bxi)$ with hidden dimensions $[128, 64]$ and ReLU activations, outputting $d(d+1)/2 = 120$ values that fill the lower triangle of $\bL$ (with $\exp(\cdot)$ on diagonal entries for positivity, followed by trace normalization). Trained via Algorithm~\ref{alg:contextual} with batch size 8, learning rate $3 \times 10^{-4}$ (Adam), gradient clipping (max norm 1.0 on encoder parameters), and early stopping with patience 400. Initialized from Learned (Static) by setting the final-layer bias to the vectorized $\bL_{\mathrm{static}}$.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Experiment 1: Decoupled Zonal Reserves}

The first experiment evaluates the framework in the simplest operational regime, where each zone independently procures reserves with no inter-zone coupling. This isolates the effect of learning the uncertainty set shape on reserve cost, with all gradients available in closed form.

Generator $i$ has dispatch $g_i$ and reserve $r_i$, with costs $c_i^g$ and $c_i^r$:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:decoupled-sced}
\begin{aligned}
\min_{g,r}\quad & \sum_{i \in \cG}(c_i^g g_i + c_i^r r_i) \\
\text{s.t.}\quad
& \sum_{i\in\cG} g_i = \sum_{b\in\cB} D_b, \\
& \underline g_i \le g_i \le \bar g_i - r_i,\ r_i\ge 0, \quad \forall i\in\cG,\\
& \sum_{i \in \cG_z} r_i \ge \rho\|\bL^\top A_z\|_2, \quad \forall z\in\cZ,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where $A_z \in \R^d$ is the transpose of the $z$-th row of $A$ (i.e., a column vector). Transmission constraints are included but non-binding in this regime (see Appendix~\ref{app:zonal-reserve}). The reserve requirement $R_z^{\min} = \rho\|\bL^\top A_z\|_2$ is an explicit function of $(\bL,\rho)$, so all gradients are closed-form via~\eqref{eq:grad-sigma-L}.

Cost and reserve values are computed at the conformally calibrated $\hat{\rho}_\tau$ for each method. For static methods, cost is deterministic given $(\bL, \hat{\rho}_\tau)$; for the contextual method, cost is averaged over the test set contexts. Reserve values (Rsv) report the total minimum requirement $\sum_z R_z^{\min}$; for the contextual method, this is averaged over test-set contexts.

