\subsection{Experiment 2: Coupled Network with Transfer Constraints}

The second experiment introduces inter-zone coupling through transfer constraints, testing whether the learned uncertainty sets remain beneficial when the dispatch problem is more tightly constrained and zones can no longer be optimized independently. Learned methods (Static and Contextual) are retrained using the coupled SCED formulation~\eqref{eq:coupled-sced}, so the learned $\bL$ differs from Experiment~1; baseline methods (Independent, Sample Covariance) use the same $\bL$ as Experiment~1.

To model inter-zone coordination, we augment the decoupled SCED~\eqref{eq:decoupled-sced} with transfer constraints that limit each zone's net export plus reserve commitment:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:coupled-sced}
\left|\sum_{i \in \cG_z} g_i - D_z\right| + \rho\|\bL^\top A_z\|_2 \leq T_z^{\max}, \quad \forall z \in \cZ_{\text{tight}},
\end{equation}
where $T_z^{\max}$ is the transfer capacity limit and $\cZ_{\text{tight}} \subseteq \cZ$ denotes zones with binding transfer constraints. The transfer limits are calibrated from the decoupled baseline: zones with the highest reserve shadow prices ($\mu_z$) receive tightened limits ($\alpha_{\text{tight}} = 0.90$), while remaining zones receive loose limits ($\alpha_{\text{loose}} = 1.50$). In this experiment, zones 5, 8, and 10 are identified as tight. Specifically, $T_z^{\max} = \alpha_z \left(\left|\sum_{i\in\cG_z} g_i^{\mathrm{base}} - D_z\right| + \hat{\rho}_\tau \|\bL_{\mathrm{base}}^\top A_z\|_2\right)$, where $(g^{\mathrm{base}}, \bL_{\mathrm{base}}, \hat{\rho}_\tau)$ come from the Sample Covariance method in Experiment~1 at $\tau = 0.95$, and $g^{\mathrm{base}}$ is the corresponding dispatch solution. These limits are fixed once from the baseline dispatch and held constant across all four methods, ensuring a controlled comparison.

Constraint~\eqref{eq:coupled-sced} introduces a transfer dual $\lambda_z$ for each tight zone. The profiled gradient (Theorem~\ref{thm:true-oracle-grad}) uses the \emph{combined} dual $(\mu_z + \lambda_z)$:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:coupled-gradient}
\nabla_{\bL} V = \sum_{z=1}^{|\cZ|} (\mu_z^* + \lambda_z^*)\, \nabla_{\bL}\, \sigma_{\cU_{\bL,\rho}}(A_z),
\end{equation}
where $\lambda_z^* = 0$ for non-tight zones. The absolute value in~\eqref{eq:coupled-sced} is implemented via two linear inequalities (Lemma~\ref{lem:robust-abs}): an upper bound $\sum_{i \in \cG_z} g_i - D_z + \rho\|\bL^\top A_z\|_2 \leq T_z^{\max}$ and a lower bound $-(\sum_{i \in \cG_z} g_i - D_z) + \rho\|\bL^\top A_z\|_2 \leq T_z^{\max}$. The transfer dual $\lambda_z^*$ is the sum of the duals on these two constraints; typically at most one binds per zone; both may bind in the degenerate case of zero net export. No modification to the envelope gradient formula (Theorem~\ref{thm:envelope}) is required---only the dual vector changes.

