Table~\ref{tab:regimes} compares the two regimes. When transmission/transfer constraints are non-binding, the problem decouples and gradients are closed-form (Experiment~1). When transfer constraints bind, one SCED solve per iteration provides the needed dual multipliers (Experiment~2).

\subsection{Limitations and Extensions}

\textbf{Distribution Shift.} Learned uncertainty sets are trained on historical data and may not generalize to extreme events or structural changes (e.g., new generation capacity). Hybrid approaches combining learned sets with worst-case bounds could provide robustness to rare events.

\textbf{Scope of Baselines.} The experiments compare four ellipsoidal uncertainty sets to isolate the effect of learning the covariance structure. Alternative geometries---budgeted polyhedral~\cite{bertsimas2004price}, Wasserstein balls~\cite{esfahani2018data}, moment-based ambiguity sets~\cite{xiong2017distributionally}---would provide complementary baselines but differ in both geometry and calibration, complicating attribution. Extension to learned non-ellipsoidal sets is a natural direction.

\textbf{Statistical Robustness.} The contextual method (Algorithm~\ref{alg:contextual}) is sensitive to initialization and random seed; results are reported for a single seed. Reporting variance across multiple seeds would strengthen the empirical evaluation of the contextual extension.

\textbf{Temporal Structure.} The current formulation treats each hour independently. Extension to multi-period unit commitment with ramping constraints is a natural direction; the envelope gradient approach extends directly, though the optimization problem becomes more complex.

\textbf{Asymmetric Uncertainty Costs.} The gauge-based uncertainty set treats all directions of forecast error symmetrically in the sense that the coverage constraint~\eqref{eq:bilevel} weights every realization equally. If certain uncertainty patterns are systematically more costly---e.g., simultaneous wind shortfalls across multiple zones during peak demand---the framework can be extended by replacing the uniform CDF $F_{\btheta}(r) = \Prob(s_{\btheta}(U) \le r)$ with a cost-weighted CDF $F_{\btheta}^w(r) = \E[w(U)\,\mathbf{1}\{s_{\btheta}(U) \le r\}]/\E[w(U)]$, where $w(U)$ assigns higher weight to more damaging realizations. The profiled gradient methodology (Theorem~\ref{thm:true-oracle-grad}) applies unchanged---only the quantile-sensitivity term is recomputed under the weighted distribution. We leave this extension for future work.

\textbf{Exchangeability and Coverage Validity.} Theorem~\ref{thm:conformal} requires exchangeability, which the VAR(1) data may violate (see Remark after Theorem~\ref{thm:consistency-eps}). Block bootstrap CIs in Table~\ref{tab:decoupled} quantify the effect of serial dependence; for rigorous finite-sample validity, block conformal methods~\cite{barber2023conformal} should be employed.

