\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper developed a differentiable robust optimization framework for learning correlated uncertainty sets in operating reserve markets. The key contributions are: (1) a profiled bilevel formulation with envelope gradients from dual multipliers, including a quantile-sensitivity correction, that avoids differentiating through the optimization solver; (2) a four-way data split with smoothed CDF estimation and conformal calibration for distribution-free coverage; and (3) demonstration on two dispatch formulations for the IEEE~118-bus system.

The decoupled experiment shows that task-aware learning reduces total cost by 4.5\% compared to conventional approaches, driven by a 47\% reduction in reserve procurement cost (\$9{,}115/hr to \$4{,}805/hr). Out-of-sample test coverage of 0.967 [0.946, 0.985] confirms that calibration-set coverage extends empirically to the test period. The coupled experiment with inter-zone transfer constraints demonstrates that learned uncertainty sets are more robust to additional operational constraints, with the learning advantage amplified by 6\% under coupling. In both regimes, the same envelope gradient formula applies---only the dual vector changes.

Future work includes multi-period formulations, neural architecture design for contextual learning, and robust extensions for extreme events.

